1
00:00:15,180 --> 00:00:17,850
[vehicle rumbling]

2
00:00:34,040 --> 00:00:35,420
[in Spanish]
Here to the right.

3
00:00:48,760 --> 00:00:49,740
Stop.

4
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:51,770
[brakes squeaking]

5
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:55,480
Stay here.

6
00:01:07,240 --> 00:01:08,820
Who's there?

7
00:01:11,240 --> 00:01:14,970
Relax, sir. We come in peace.

8
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:16,210
Stay right there!

9
00:01:18,420 --> 00:01:19,710
Relax.

10
00:01:27,720 --> 00:01:29,470
How are the cows?

11
00:01:46,780 --> 00:01:48,780
[rain patters softly outside]

12
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,390
The cops came here... a few months ago.

13
00:02:00,420 --> 00:02:02,000
What did you tell them?

14
00:02:02,840 --> 00:02:04,250
The truth.

15
00:02:07,220 --> 00:02:09,800
That I haven't seen you in years.

16
00:02:13,930 --> 00:02:16,220
You've gotten old, Pablo.

17
00:02:19,850 --> 00:02:20,900
[sighs]

18
00:02:21,900 --> 00:02:23,270
It happens.

19
00:02:24,230 --> 00:02:25,820
You look younger.

20
00:02:26,780 --> 00:02:29,380
It happens. [chuckles]

21
00:02:29,400 --> 00:02:33,910
Life in the country keeps you young.

22
00:02:37,700 --> 00:02:39,910
Be careful, it's hot.

23
00:02:41,710 --> 00:02:43,460
What's your name?

24
00:02:45,840 --> 00:02:47,010
Limón, sir.

25
00:02:47,670 --> 00:02:51,030
Don't give me that shit.
What's your real name?

26
00:02:51,050 --> 00:02:53,150
- Jhon.
- Jhon.

27
00:02:53,180 --> 00:02:55,610
Do you know how to milk a cow, Jhon?

28
00:02:55,640 --> 00:02:58,930
- No, sir.
- Well, you better learn.

29
00:03:02,020 --> 00:03:03,900
All right, gentlemen.

30
00:03:05,770 --> 00:03:08,070
I get up at 5:00 a.m.

31
00:03:09,530 --> 00:03:10,990
Good night.

32
00:03:11,860 --> 00:03:13,570
Good night, Dad.

33
00:03:16,120 --> 00:03:19,160
[Latin guitar theme music plays]

34
00:04:47,630 --> 00:04:51,210
[Steve] I read in a book somewhere
about a rich guy who goes broke.

35
00:04:52,460 --> 00:04:56,720
When he's asked how it happened,
how he had lost everything, he answered:

36
00:04:57,510 --> 00:05:02,520
"Slowly at first.
And then... all at once."

37
00:05:04,060 --> 00:05:07,350
For Pablo Escobar,
"all at once" had finally come.

38
00:05:08,610 --> 00:05:12,840
His empire in shambles,
his army all dead or in jail,

39
00:05:12,860 --> 00:05:17,820
Escobar did the one thing
he could still do: a disappearing act.

40
00:05:18,700 --> 00:05:21,530
One month, 14 days and seven hours...

41
00:05:22,450 --> 00:05:26,120
with no sightings, no intercepts, nothing.

42
00:05:27,210 --> 00:05:30,350
While we waited
for his eventual reemergence,

43
00:05:30,380 --> 00:05:33,250
the machine built to capture him
found itself idle.

44
00:05:34,630 --> 00:05:37,090
And that brought
a different kind of danger.

45
00:05:38,050 --> 00:05:40,510
One that comes
with too much time to think.

46
00:05:42,350 --> 00:05:45,890
Some started to look inward
at the path we had taken to get here...

47
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:51,110
asking, "How much of this blood is on me,
and how do I get clean?"

48
00:05:51,730 --> 00:05:54,840
[in Spanish]
It is the state, not individuals,

49
00:05:54,860 --> 00:05:58,800
that has justice in its hands
and the legitimacy to use arms.

50
00:05:58,820 --> 00:06:00,510
[Steve]
Under mounting political pressure,

51
00:06:00,530 --> 00:06:03,580
Gaviria finally publicly denounced
Los Pepes.

52
00:06:04,330 --> 00:06:07,160
And Los Pepes responded
with their own press release.

53
00:06:07,910 --> 00:06:09,850
They said their job was done.

54
00:06:09,870 --> 00:06:12,500
They were packing up and going home.

55
00:06:13,210 --> 00:06:16,510
But Los Pepes wasn't something
you could turn on and off.

56
00:06:17,090 --> 00:06:19,190
Its members were looking to the future.

57
00:06:19,220 --> 00:06:23,260
One without Escobar.
And they each had their own version of it.

58
00:06:23,850 --> 00:06:26,910
Los Pepes had knocked Pablo
out of the narco business

59
00:06:26,930 --> 00:06:30,950
and that had created a vacancy
for a new cocaine king of Medellín.

60
00:06:30,980 --> 00:06:34,880
Or, depending on who you asked,
maybe a queen.

61
00:06:34,900 --> 00:06:38,710
[in Spanish] Gilberto's no longer
our partner. I don't care what he thinks.

62
00:06:38,740 --> 00:06:40,670
Have you seen the news?

63
00:06:40,700 --> 00:06:43,720
They issued a statement without us.

64
00:06:43,740 --> 00:06:45,700
Los Pepes is done.

65
00:06:46,700 --> 00:06:50,180
That's only for show.
The Castaños are still in Medellín.

66
00:06:50,210 --> 00:06:51,420
Hmm?

67
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:53,380
No one told me anything.

68
00:06:54,750 --> 00:06:56,770
Listen to me, Berna.

69
00:06:56,800 --> 00:07:00,150
If Escobar comes through that door,
we'll kill him ourselves.

70
00:07:00,170 --> 00:07:02,050
We don't need anybody else.

71
00:07:02,840 --> 00:07:04,570
Start moving this product now.

72
00:07:04,600 --> 00:07:06,430
That's all fine, Judy.

73
00:07:07,270 --> 00:07:09,280
But if Gilberto finds out, what then?

74
00:07:09,310 --> 00:07:13,350
Did you know they're offering
$1.4 million for Los Pepes?

75
00:07:14,110 --> 00:07:15,730
I know where they are.

76
00:07:18,740 --> 00:07:20,990
[softly] Be careful what you say.

77
00:07:21,650 --> 00:07:24,530
That's a dangerous thought, Judy.

78
00:07:25,200 --> 00:07:27,290
I'm not interested in the reward.

79
00:07:28,160 --> 00:07:30,120
I'm interested in my labs.

80
00:07:32,120 --> 00:07:34,210
Then at least tell Gilberto yourself.

81
00:07:40,380 --> 00:07:41,380
[man] Sir?

82
00:07:45,050 --> 00:07:46,100
Hello.

83
00:07:48,560 --> 00:07:50,910
And to what do I owe this lovely surprise?

84
00:07:50,930 --> 00:07:54,080
We're at the warehouse in Manrique.

85
00:07:54,100 --> 00:07:55,830
This place is full of product.

86
00:07:55,860 --> 00:07:58,330
What do you want us to do?
Where do we send it?

87
00:07:58,360 --> 00:08:02,500
Keep it. Think of it as a contribution
to your great cause

88
00:08:02,530 --> 00:08:04,920
against the communists in the jungle.

89
00:08:04,950 --> 00:08:09,390
I'm sure you'll find its value
can be put to good use.

90
00:08:09,410 --> 00:08:10,800
And what do we do about Judy?

91
00:08:10,830 --> 00:08:13,180
Do whatever you think is best.

92
00:08:13,210 --> 00:08:16,750
Well, Gilberto, if you say so.
Thank you very much.

93
00:08:18,460 --> 00:08:22,820
Fidel. Gilberto said
we can keep all of it.

94
00:08:22,840 --> 00:08:28,970
What? I thought we were going home.
We don't know anything about cocaine.

95
00:08:30,060 --> 00:08:32,120
We'll learn.

96
00:08:32,140 --> 00:08:34,600
If they can, why not us?

97
00:08:35,730 --> 00:08:37,900
And what about Judy? Hmm?

98
00:08:40,320 --> 00:08:43,780
Judy feels Medellín
is only big enough for one narco.

99
00:08:44,610 --> 00:08:48,130
We'll let the Castaños decide which one.

100
00:08:48,160 --> 00:08:52,470
[Steve] Los Pepes may have disbanded,
but that didn't mean they were done.

101
00:08:52,500 --> 00:08:57,170
The story of a vigilante army taking down
Escobar made for great headlines.

102
00:08:57,750 --> 00:09:01,940
And while no one was named, it's not
to say it wasn't cause for concern.

103
00:09:01,960 --> 00:09:04,510
Yes, ma'am, as far as I know.

104
00:09:05,220 --> 00:09:07,610
No, we're, uh, crystal clear on that.

105
00:09:07,640 --> 00:09:10,010
- [whispers] Messina.
- [silent mouthing]

106
00:09:11,470 --> 00:09:12,850
Yeah. Uh, he just got in.

107
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:20,710
- Hey, boss.
- [Messina] Murphy fill you in?

108
00:09:20,730 --> 00:09:21,730
Yeah.

109
00:09:22,610 --> 00:09:25,250
This article's getting more traction
than we thought.

110
00:09:25,280 --> 00:09:28,800
International news outlets keep calling,
want a statement from the ambassador.

111
00:09:28,820 --> 00:09:31,220
- Are we giving one?
- No. Nobody is.

112
00:09:31,240 --> 00:09:32,430
But we're watching it closely.

113
00:09:32,450 --> 00:09:35,310
I don't need to tell you
it could look very bad for us.

114
00:09:35,330 --> 00:09:36,770
I want to make sure we're covered.

115
00:09:36,790 --> 00:09:39,180
Well, Los Pepes is disbanded.
It's basically over.

116
00:09:39,210 --> 00:09:43,440
Look, I tend to agree. But the press may
shake a few more trees, see what falls.

117
00:09:43,460 --> 00:09:44,650
What if someone talks?

118
00:09:44,670 --> 00:09:47,720
The only people that are gonna
talk about Los Pepes is Los Pepes.

119
00:09:48,510 --> 00:09:49,740
And they're not talking.

120
00:09:49,760 --> 00:09:51,780
So we're covered.

121
00:09:51,800 --> 00:09:53,100
We better be.

122
00:09:55,270 --> 00:09:56,870
- Fabian.
- [in Spanish] Yes?

123
00:09:56,890 --> 00:09:59,830
- Bring the Mercedes. Thank you.
- Yes, ma'am. Right away.

124
00:09:59,850 --> 00:10:01,400
Hurry up, Berna.

125
00:10:02,940 --> 00:10:06,590
Relax, Judy.
That meeting can't start without you.

126
00:10:06,610 --> 00:10:08,170
Mmm-hmm.

127
00:10:08,200 --> 00:10:10,590
How many people do we have
in the laboratories?

128
00:10:10,620 --> 00:10:14,720
- Forty-five in each one.
- How many supervisors?

129
00:10:14,740 --> 00:10:16,410
Three in each.

130
00:10:17,330 --> 00:10:20,580
- We need twice as many shifts.
- Yes, ma'am.

131
00:10:21,250 --> 00:10:24,270
Oscar, Luis! Get in the cars.
The boss is leaving.

132
00:10:24,300 --> 00:10:25,340
[man] Yes, sir.

133
00:10:27,800 --> 00:10:30,550
[men shouting]

134
00:10:32,260 --> 00:10:33,550
[indistinct]

135
00:10:36,520 --> 00:10:38,680
[dialogue distant, muted]

136
00:10:39,810 --> 00:10:41,900
[audio distorted]

137
00:10:46,900 --> 00:10:49,030
[phone ringing]

138
00:10:54,950 --> 00:10:56,660
- Peña.
- [Berna] Javier.

139
00:10:58,120 --> 00:11:00,890
- [in Spanish] What do you want?
- Something happened, we need to talk.

140
00:11:00,920 --> 00:11:02,480
I'm busy. I can't talk.

141
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:04,590
There's been an attempt on Judy.

142
00:11:06,090 --> 00:11:09,800
She's saying a few things
you might want to hear.

143
00:11:15,220 --> 00:11:16,430
Give me time.

144
00:11:19,230 --> 00:11:20,230
What's going on?

145
00:11:22,440 --> 00:11:24,480
Nothing that's my problem anymore.

146
00:11:26,320 --> 00:11:27,480
Where you going?

147
00:11:28,320 --> 00:11:29,650
I just want to make sure.

148
00:11:34,370 --> 00:11:35,990
Fuck it. I don't want to know.

149
00:11:46,540 --> 00:11:48,670
- Peña.
- [in Spanish] Mr. Peña has arrived.

150
00:11:49,800 --> 00:11:52,300
Let's go. Search.

151
00:12:20,700 --> 00:12:25,480
Kiko and I built all of this together.
This is all that is left for me.

152
00:12:25,500 --> 00:12:30,270
What are the Castaños thinking?
That they can chase me out?

153
00:12:30,300 --> 00:12:32,110
I'm not leaving.

154
00:12:32,130 --> 00:12:34,220
They don't want you to leave,
they want to kill you.

155
00:12:35,180 --> 00:12:40,310
And what about you?
You're in this with me too.

156
00:12:45,850 --> 00:12:51,920
Look... you brought these guys here.
You got in bed with Cali.

157
00:12:51,940 --> 00:12:54,130
This is all your doing.

158
00:12:54,150 --> 00:12:57,090
This is a fight between narcos.
It's not my problem.

159
00:12:57,110 --> 00:12:58,990
Don't call me again.

160
00:13:00,580 --> 00:13:04,680
Berna, last I heard, leaking classified
intelligence is a federal offense.

161
00:13:04,710 --> 00:13:07,980
Especially when it ends up
in the hands of a death squad

162
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:09,560
that's killed innocent people.

163
00:13:09,590 --> 00:13:14,670
I'm sure some newspaper in America might
be interested in hearing more about that.

164
00:13:17,260 --> 00:13:18,530
Are you threatening me?

165
00:13:18,550 --> 00:13:21,680
Yes, I'm threatening you.

166
00:13:28,770 --> 00:13:30,360
You gotta be fucking kidding me.

167
00:13:32,480 --> 00:13:33,790
What do you want?

168
00:13:33,820 --> 00:13:35,530
You're a cop.

169
00:13:36,780 --> 00:13:39,760
You know perfectly well
where Montecasino is.

170
00:13:39,780 --> 00:13:42,490
Where the Castaños are,
and the Rodriguezes.

171
00:13:43,410 --> 00:13:44,790
Arrest them.

172
00:13:45,620 --> 00:13:48,670
And when you do,
accidentally shoot them in the head.

173
00:13:49,540 --> 00:13:53,550
- It doesn't work that way.
- Oh, no? Then how?

174
00:14:04,180 --> 00:14:05,930
We'll do it my way.

175
00:14:07,100 --> 00:14:10,960
[Berna]
So you want Judy to be a rat?

176
00:14:10,980 --> 00:14:12,650
I don't agree with this, Javier.

177
00:14:13,860 --> 00:14:16,150
We are narcos, but we have our honor.

178
00:14:16,860 --> 00:14:22,160
Berna... you're a fucking drug dealer
who sells poison by the kilo.

179
00:14:23,660 --> 00:14:25,600
Fuck your honor.

180
00:14:25,620 --> 00:14:26,870
[soft chuckle]

181
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:29,520
Says you.

182
00:14:29,540 --> 00:14:33,170
You've been happily working
with the information we've provided.

183
00:14:34,130 --> 00:14:36,300
And what have you done?

184
00:14:38,420 --> 00:14:41,050
If you have a better idea, go for it.

185
00:14:41,930 --> 00:14:44,740
Otherwise, this is the deal.

186
00:14:44,760 --> 00:14:47,180
Judy becomes a confidential informant
to the DEA.

187
00:14:47,810 --> 00:14:50,600
She gives us Cali, everything she knows.

188
00:14:51,560 --> 00:14:56,570
If you don't like it,
you can take on the Castaños alone.

189
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:00,450
[in English]
And you can go fuck yourself.

190
00:15:01,450 --> 00:15:03,550
[Steve]
Best way to make a bad story go away

191
00:15:03,570 --> 00:15:05,330
is to come up with a better story...

192
00:15:06,120 --> 00:15:07,750
and sell it hard.

193
00:15:08,410 --> 00:15:11,430
This is one of the cornerstones
of American foreign policy,

194
00:15:11,460 --> 00:15:15,150
and one we learned through years
of trial and error in Latin America,

195
00:15:15,170 --> 00:15:18,770
Chile, Guatemala, Panama.

196
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:21,360
Getting caught with your pants down sucks,

197
00:15:21,380 --> 00:15:23,990
but if at the same time
you give the folks a big win,

198
00:15:24,010 --> 00:15:28,580
like, say, dismantling the second biggest
drug cartel in the world,

199
00:15:28,600 --> 00:15:31,580
well, then nobody's paying attention
to the bad story.

200
00:15:31,600 --> 00:15:33,960
They're too busy patting you on the back.

201
00:15:33,980 --> 00:15:39,290
Risky plan? Yes.
But pressure will force you to take risks.

202
00:15:39,320 --> 00:15:41,670
It'll force you to do a lot of things.

203
00:15:41,700 --> 00:15:44,370
[in Spanish] We haven't heard anything
from him for weeks.

204
00:15:46,240 --> 00:15:47,800
We don't even know where he is.

205
00:15:47,830 --> 00:15:50,600
[Hermilda] I don't know why
you're letting De Greiff come here.

206
00:15:50,620 --> 00:15:52,410
He's coming to scare you.

207
00:15:53,080 --> 00:15:55,600
And now you're losing faith in Pablo.

208
00:15:55,630 --> 00:15:58,800
[gentle scoff]
You don't understand, do you?

209
00:16:01,880 --> 00:16:04,280
We don't have any more money, Hermilda.

210
00:16:04,300 --> 00:16:07,240
If they take our protection away,
we can't do anything else.

211
00:16:07,260 --> 00:16:10,870
Pablo has many properties.
Don't be so dramatic, Tata.

212
00:16:10,890 --> 00:16:13,370
You think someone
is going to invest in us?

213
00:16:13,390 --> 00:16:15,520
They're going to give us their money?

214
00:16:20,860 --> 00:16:22,610
No one is going to help us.

215
00:16:23,780 --> 00:16:25,950
Everyone knows what that would mean.

216
00:16:38,340 --> 00:16:40,420
Whatever he's doing...

217
00:16:41,630 --> 00:16:46,050
wherever my son is,
he's doing it for his family.

218
00:16:47,300 --> 00:16:48,800
Don't forget that.

219
00:17:13,950 --> 00:17:20,670
[softly] Pablo? Pablo?
Can you hear me, Pablo? Please answer.

220
00:17:23,840 --> 00:17:25,840
[bird calling in distance]

221
00:17:28,550 --> 00:17:30,510
- [goat bleating]
- [cow mooing]

222
00:17:34,060 --> 00:17:37,160
- [radio static]
- [Pablo] Tata, can you hear me?

223
00:17:37,190 --> 00:17:39,100
[static]

224
00:17:40,860 --> 00:17:41,980
Tata?

225
00:17:44,440 --> 00:17:45,940
Can you hear me?

226
00:17:46,570 --> 00:17:48,070
[static]

227
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:58,080
[men chattering outside]

228
00:18:27,690 --> 00:18:28,860
[grunts]

229
00:18:50,180 --> 00:18:52,260
[grunting]

230
00:19:01,600 --> 00:19:05,040
[Miguel] That's a lot of product for men
who don't know how to run this business.

231
00:19:05,070 --> 00:19:09,880
We have to be clear with them.
Their work isn't done.

232
00:19:09,900 --> 00:19:12,110
Our donation to them is an advance.

233
00:19:13,200 --> 00:19:15,840
Besides, we have to keep them happy.

234
00:19:15,870 --> 00:19:19,640
Their connection with the Americans
is invaluable, brother.

235
00:19:19,660 --> 00:19:21,680
What a fucking joke,

236
00:19:21,710 --> 00:19:25,020
the CIA and their war
against the communists.

237
00:19:25,040 --> 00:19:29,840
It's a joke, but that friendship
could save our lives one day.

238
00:19:31,550 --> 00:19:34,070
What? Any news about Judy?

239
00:19:34,090 --> 00:19:38,990
The Castaños took their first shot,
a bomb. But they didn't kill her.

240
00:19:39,020 --> 00:19:42,540
Since when did it get so fucking hard
to kill someone?

241
00:19:42,560 --> 00:19:46,830
What about her assistant?
The fat one, what do they call him? Berna?

242
00:19:46,860 --> 00:19:49,920
He's the one we should kill.
She's just a loud-mouth bitch.

243
00:19:49,940 --> 00:19:53,360
Don Berna. Him we found.

244
00:19:54,110 --> 00:19:55,320
Where?

245
00:19:55,950 --> 00:19:57,240
Here.

246
00:19:57,990 --> 00:19:59,620
Out front.

247
00:20:09,760 --> 00:20:11,300
[Gilberto]
Don Berna!

248
00:20:14,050 --> 00:20:15,780
Welcome to Cali.

249
00:20:15,800 --> 00:20:18,620
Gilberto, thank you, brother.

250
00:20:18,640 --> 00:20:21,480
Forgive us, but we weren't expecting you.

251
00:20:22,980 --> 00:20:26,440
